Yesterday, senior officials from the White House, Department of Defense, and Department of Homeland Security participated in the 27th plenary meeting of the Council of Governors. The meeting discussed upcoming initiatives and priorities in areas such as cybersecurity, emergency management and disaster preparedness, military support, and workforce development. Opening remarks were provided by Secretary of Homeland Security Alejandro Mayorkas, White House Homeland Security Advisor Dr. Liz Sherwood-Randall, Deputy Secretary of Defense Dr. Kathleen Hicks, and Senior Advisor to the President and Director of Intergovernmental Affairs Tom Perez. Governors from Minnesota, Delaware, Michigan, Wyoming, New Mexico, and Indiana were also present. The meeting also included an overview of strategic budget trends and an update on the Department of Defense's forthcoming Homeland Defense Policy Guidance. The Council also discussed "long-term recovery and rebuilding" efforts, with Sherwood-Randall providing an overview of the Administration's ongoing work in supporting communities in becoming more prepared for disasters and rebuilding faster and better after them. The Governors and Administration officials committed to working closely together in advancing this effort. The Council of Governors was authorized in 2008 and focuses on matters of homeland security, defense, civil support, synchronization and integration of state and Federal military activities, and other mutual interests involving the National Guard.